oung working-class women who have little cultural capital to enable class mobility; to the fact that analyses of class too often remain insufficiently transformed by feminist, ethnic, and queer studies; and to the failure of some feminist theory itself to theorize women as class subjects.Women without Class makes a case for analytical and political attention to class, but not at the expense of attention to other social formations.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChildren, WhitezCaliforniazSan Francisco Bay AreaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aMexican American teenage girlsxRace identityzCalifornia. 0aMexican American teenage girlszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 0aTeenage girls, WhitexRace identityzCalifornia. 0aTeenage girls, WhitezCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 4aanthropologist. 4acalifornia women. 4acentral valley. 4aclass performance. 4aclass theory. 4acolor. 4acoming of age. 4acontemporary movement. 4acultural reference. 4acultural theory. 4aethnicity. 4agender. 4ahistorical context. 4aincome disparity. 4amexican-american women. 4asexuality. 4asociologists. 4atheorists. 4awhite girls. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520957244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520957244.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-